folder: Bushwick Avenue & Stagg Street, Brooklyn, NY
text:
Bushwick Ave., at the N.E. corner of Stagg Street, showing the 50th Police Precinct station house, once known as the 6th., which occupies land owned by the heirs of Charles Schenck in 1855.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

folder: Bushwick Avenue & Stagg Street, Brooklyn, NY
text:
(1)
Bushwick Ave., east side, north from Stagg Street, showing St. Catherine's (R.C.) Hospital in the center of view.

March 1929.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, showing also the west side of the street. Note the area of demolished homes to be replaced by low cost apartments.

October 27, 1936.

P. L. Sperr.

folder: Stagg Street & Bushwick Avenue, Brooklyn, NY
text:
Stage Street, north side, just east of Bushwick Avenue. Shown is a new addition to Public School No. 35, this being Ten Eyck Street, looking east.

Board of Education of the City of New York

June 24, 1931

folder: Stagg Street & Bushwick Avenue, Brooklyn, NY
text:
229 Stagg Street, north side, near the N.W. corner of Bushwick Ave., showing an old frame house in the rear of No. 229, beyond which is seen a partial view of P.S. No. 36, and the bell tower of St. Catherine's Hospital.

September 26, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

folder: Bushwick Avenue & Stagg Street, Brooklyn, NY
text:
Bushwick Ave., west side, south fromi Stagg Street. More demolition to make way for low rental housing. Federal Funds are making it possible. At the right, is Public School No. 17, on Stagg Street.
July 30, 1935.
P. L. Sperr.
